  abstract = {Environmental changes are responsible for the evolution of flexible physiology and the extent of phenotypic plasticity in the regulation of birds' organ size has not been appreciated until recently. Rapid reversible physiological changes during different life\textendash history stages are virtually only known from long\textendash distance migrants, and few studies have focused on less extreme aspects of organ flexibility. During moult, birds suffer from increased wing loading due to wing\textendash area reductions, which may impair flight ability. A previous study found that tree sparrows' escape flight (Passer montanus) is unaffected during moult, suggesting compensatory aptness. We used non\textendash invasive techniques to study physiological adaptations to increased wing loading in tree sparrows. As wing area was reduced during natural moult the ratio of pectoral\textendash muscle size to body mass increased. When moult was completed this ratio decreased. We show experimentally a novel, strategic, organ\textendash flexibility pattern. Unlike the general pattern, where body mass is positively coupled to pectoral\textendash muscle size, tree sparrows responded within 7 days to reductions in wing area by reducing body mass concurrently with an increase in pectoral\textendash muscle size. This rapid flexibility in a non\textendash migratory species probably reflects the paramount importance and long history of flight in birds.},
